08","about 1441":"circa 1441","1516":"1516","Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England":"Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1441–1522":"about 1441–1522","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1441–1522":"1441–1522","1446–1483":"1446–1483","1448–Female":"1448–Deceased","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1459–1498":"1459–1498","1408–Male":"1408–Deceased","1424–Female":"1424–Deceased","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1350":"1350","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1424":"1424","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1441":"1441","1408":"1408","about 1441":"about 1441","1516":"1516","Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England":"Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bentall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name, status name from either of two places called Benthall in Shrops."],"variants":[{"name":"Bendle","meanings":["English: variant of   Bendall   or   Benthall  .","In some cases an altered form of German   Bendel  ."]},{"name":"Bentle","meanings":["In some cases possibly an Americanized form of South German   Bentele  .","English (Yorkshire): perhaps an altered form of   Bendle   or a variant of   Bentley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Benthall","meanings":["English: habitational name from one of two places in Shropshire named Benthall, from Old English <i>beonet</i> ‘bent grass’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’."]},{"name":"Bendall","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Binhall in Frethern and Saul in Gloucestershire, or perhaps a habitational name from Benhall in Suffolk.","perhaps a variant of   Benthall  ."]},{"name":"Bendell","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Bendall   or   Benthall  .","In some cases probably an altered form of German   Bendel  ."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":14,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna Bentall was born about 1441, in Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England, her father, John Benthall, was 34 and her mother, Cecily Wolrich, was 18. She had at least 1 daughter with John Hunt. She died in 1522, at the age of 82."},"et":{"about 1441–1522":"umbes 1441–1522","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1441–1522":"1441–1522","1446–1483":"1446–1483","1448–Female":"1448–Surnud","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1459–1498":"1459–1498","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1424–Female":"1424–Surnud","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1350":"1350","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1424":"1424","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1441":"1441","1408":"1408","about 1441":"umbes 1441","1516":"1516","Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England":"Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1441–1522":"noin 1441–1522","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1441–1522":"1441–1522","1446–1483":"1446–1483","1448–Female":"1448–Kuollut","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1459–1498":"1459–1498","1408–Male":"1408–Kuollut","1424–Female":"1424–Kuollut","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1350":"1350","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1424":"1424","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1441":"1441","1408":"1408","about 1441":"noin 1441","1516":"1516","Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, England":"Nuneham Courtenay, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1441–1522":"environ 1441–1522","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1441–1522":"1441–1522","1446–1483":"1446–1483","1448–Female":"1448–Décédée","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1459–1498":"1459–1498","1408–Male":"1408–Décédé","1424–Female":"1424–Décédée","1440":"1440","1483":"1483","1350":"1350","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1424":"1424","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1498":"1498","1441":"1441","1408"